# Dialog Window Standards

- Always build dialog windows with `@front-end/src/components/ui/custom-dialog.tsx` (`CustomDialog`).
- Do not use raw Radix/HTML dialog containers directly in feature pages when `CustomDialog` can be used.
- Every dialog must render a visible header and a visible footer.
- All action/control buttons (for example: Cancel, Save, Next, Previous, Submit, Delete, Confirm) must be rendered in the dialog footer.
- Do not place primary or secondary action buttons inside the dialog body/content area.
- Footer action buttons must use auto width based on their content text.
- Do not force footer action buttons to full width (for example, avoid `w-full` or `flex-1` on footer buttons unless explicitly required by the feature).

## Theme and accents

- Use project theme tokens and accent styles for dialog UI (for example: `bg-background`, `text-foreground`, `text-muted-foreground`, `border-[var(--glass-border)]`, and accent-aware variants).
- Keep dialog visuals consistent with existing theme behavior in light/dark modes.

## Reusability

- Prefer reusable UI components from `front-end/src/components/ui` for inputs, buttons, labels, and related controls.
- Extract repeated dialog sections into reusable local/shared components instead of duplicating markup and logic.
- Store each dialog in its own dedicated folder with a meaningful, descriptive name.
- Avoid placing multiple unrelated dialog implementations in one large file when they can be split into focused dialog folders/components.

## Wizard dialogs

- If the dialog is a wizard (multi-step flow), show a visible step progress bar.
- If a dialog is a wizard, implement each step as a separate component (one component per step) instead of one large inline render block.
- Progress bar width must be half of the dialog content area (`w-1/2`).
- Progress bar must be horizontally centered (for example: container with `mx-auto` and centered alignment).
- Render only one primary step progress indicator in wizard dialogs.
- Do not render both a progress bar and a numeric/circle stepper at the same time.
- Keep step progress visually aligned with the active step and theme accents.

## Tabbed dialogs

- If a dialog has tabs, implement each tab as a separate component (one component per tab) instead of one large inline tab render block.
- Organize tab components in dedicated folders when tab logic/UI is complex; keep simpler tabs as focused sibling components when appropriate.
- In tabbed dialogs, tab-level action/control buttons are allowed inside the tab body when they are scoped to tab content (for example: Add item, Edit selected item, Delete selected item).
- Keep global dialog actions (for example: Cancel, Save, Submit, Confirm) in the dialog footer; tab-level actions must not replace required footer actions.
- For tab list rows/items, provide a 3-dot menu (`MoreVertical`/kebab menu) for item-specific functions.
- 3-dot item menus should include context actions such as Edit/Delete (and other item-scoped functions when needed), styled with project theme/accent tokens.
